A '''couple interview''' (or '''joint couple interview''', or more broadly '''conjoint interview''', '''joint interview''' or '''dyadic interview''') is a method of [[qualitative research]] used in the [[social sciences]], where two [[spouse]]s are [[Interview (research)|interviewed]] together.<ref name="B-F-2012" /> Such an interview is typically [[Semi-structured interview|semi-structured]] or [[Unstructured interview|unstructured]]. Couple interviews are important in [[household]] research, often from a [[psychology|psychological]], [[sociology|sociological]], [[social anthropology|anthropological]] or [[Social geography|social geographical]] perspective, and are also frequently used within health research.<ref name="P-G-2015" /> A couple interview is a form of joint interviewing (interviews involving two interviewees), the subject of a growing methodological research literature.<ref name="B-F-2012" /><ref name="P-G-2015">{{cite journal |last1=Polak |first1=L |last2= Green |first2= J |year= 2015|title=Using Joint Interviews to Add Analytic Value |journal=[[Qualitative Health Research]] |volume=|issue= |pages=|publisher= |doi= 10.1177/1049732315580103 }}</ref>

There is an ongoing methodological controversy over whether couples should ideally be interviewed together or apart.<ref name="B-F-2012">{{cite journal |last1=Bjørnholt |first1=M |last2= Farstad |first2= G.R. |year= 2012|title='Am I rambling?' On the advantages of interviewing couples together |journal=[[Qualitative Research]] |volume=14|issue=1 |pages=3–19|publisher= |doi= 10.1177/1468794112459671 |url=http://www.margunnbjornholt.no/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Am_I_rambling_on_the_advantages_of_interviewing_couples_together.pdf | format = PDF }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Valentine |first1=G |last2= |first2= |year= 1999|title= Doing household research: Interviewing couples together and apart|journal=[[Area (journal)|Area]] |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=67–74 |publisher= |doi= 10.1111/j.1475-4762.1999.tb00172.x |url= }}</ref> Bjørnholt and Farstad argue that the couple interview should be seen as a distinct form of the qualitative research interview, and argue that the couple interview has several advantages over individual interviews, in particular in "solving the [[Research ethics|ethical]] problems of [[anonymity]] and [[consent]] among interviewees, and [resulting] in the production of rich data, including observational data," and in intra-couple dynamics and the [[Social interaction|interaction]] between the informants, as well as with the researcher(s), in the interview situation, which may also reveal controversies and areas of conflict, by providing a reflective space for both partners together, which enables them to challenge as well as to reinforce each other's accounts.<ref name="B-F-2012" /> They further argue that the researcher plays an important role, as couple interviews may be seen as an arena of "family display,"<ref name="B-F-2012" /> using a concept originally proposed by [[Janet Finch]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Finch |first1=J |last2= |first2= |year= 2007|title= Displaying Families|journal=[[Sociology (journal)|Sociology]] |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=65–81 |publisher= |doi= 10.1177/0038038507072284 |url= }}</ref> The opportunity to observe shared storytelling is regarded as a widely documented advantage of joint interviewing.<ref name="B-F-2012" />

